<figureCitation box="[973,1137,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–121" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,203,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[153,1433,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 118–121. Male genitalia of Simplimorpha (Myrtinepticula) kailai Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide AD935 (ZMUC). 118, capsule with phallus removed, ventral view; 119, same, dorsal view; 120, 121, phallus" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609759/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Figs. 120, 121</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1149,1192,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 122–125" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[153,1433,193,1913]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 122–125. Simplimorpha (Myrtinepticula) kailai Stonis, sp. nov. 122, male genitalia, slide AD935, ventral view of capsule; 123, same, dorsal view of capsule; 124, same, phallus; 125, habitat, disturbed tropical premontane forest (south western Amazonian selva), elevation ca. 700 m, Peru, Junín Region, Satipo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609761/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">124</figureCitation>
) 220 µm long, 25–35 µm broad (15 µm at base); vesica without cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,943,548,573]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,548,573]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Bionomics</emphasis>
. Adults fly in November. Otherwise biology unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="173" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,583,608]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Distribution</emphasis>
. This species occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[611,665,584,607]" name="Peru" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Peru</collectingCountry>
, in the tropical premontane forest of the southwestern Amazon Basin at an elevation of about 
<quantity box="[421,492,620,645]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="750.0">750 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[507,605,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 122–125" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[153,1433,193,1913]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 122–125. Simplimorpha (Myrtinepticula) kailai Stonis, sp. nov. 122, male genitalia, slide AD935, ventral view of capsule; 123, same, dorsal view of capsule; 124, same, phallus; 125, habitat, disturbed tropical premontane forest (south western Amazonian selva), elevation ca. 700 m, Peru, Junín Region, Satipo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609761/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Fig. 125</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="173" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,655,680]" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Etymology.</emphasis>
This peculiar new species is named in honor of Dr. Lauri Kaila, a Senior Curator at the Finnish Museum of Natural History, University of Helsinki (
<collectingCountry box="[748,839,692,717]" name="Finland" pageId="22" pageNumber="173">Finland</collectingCountry>
), mostly working on Gelechioidea, and probably the greatest expert on the wing venation of microlepidoptera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
